1
00:00:39,039 --> 00:00:42,000
<i>I'm sure you're aware Japan's ratio</i>
<i>of determining the cause of death</i>

2
00:00:42,083 --> 00:00:43,710
is much lower than in other countries?

3
00:00:43,793 --> 00:00:44,627
Yes.

4
00:00:44,711 --> 00:00:46,045
To improve that,

5
00:00:46,129 --> 00:00:51,885
we're going to experimentally introduce
the American medical examiner system.

6
00:00:52,594 --> 00:00:54,262
Medical examiner?

7
00:00:54,345 --> 00:00:57,766
The biggest difference from Japan's system
is that medical examiners,

8
00:00:57,849 --> 00:01:01,519
<i>or forensic pathologists,</i>
<i>have investigative authority.</i>

9
00:01:16,868 --> 00:01:17,827
What?

10
00:01:18,369 --> 00:01:22,916
Does that mean doctors
can investigate cases like the police?

11
00:01:22,999 --> 00:01:25,627
No, not in exactly the same way,

12
00:01:25,710 --> 00:01:28,838
<i>but they can conduct investigations</i>
<i>to determine the cause of death.</i>

13
00:01:28,922 --> 00:01:31,674
<i>They also have the authority</i>
<i>to determine the need for an autopsy.</i>

14
00:01:33,802 --> 00:01:35,512
I see…

15
00:01:54,405 --> 00:01:55,323
<i>So,</i>

16
00:01:55,406 --> 00:01:57,826
<i>we're bringing in Dr. Masumi Mizusawa,</i>

17
00:01:57,909 --> 00:02:00,787
<i>who has worked as a medical examiner</i>
<i>in the US for 15 years.</i>

18
00:02:00,870 --> 00:02:02,163
And Ms. Kiryu,

19
00:02:02,247 --> 00:02:05,750
you'll be the director
of Medical Examiner Japan.

20
00:02:06,251 --> 00:02:07,252
Okay.

21
00:02:09,879 --> 00:02:10,797
What?

22
00:02:37,365 --> 00:02:39,242
Why am I being demoted?

23
00:02:39,325 --> 00:02:41,202
I mean, there's no way a policy change

24
00:02:41,286 --> 00:02:44,080
is going to increase the rate
of determining the cause of death.

25
00:02:44,956 --> 00:02:46,332
And you know,

26
00:02:46,416 --> 00:02:49,711
I became a bureaucrat
because I wanted to create systems

27
00:02:49,794 --> 00:02:52,755
that let everyone in this country
live their lives smiling.

28
00:02:53,339 --> 00:02:55,341
This topic is not even my specialty.

29
00:02:55,425 --> 00:02:56,968
I don't have the knowledge.

30
00:02:57,051 --> 00:02:59,178
And I'm supposed to be in charge on-site?

31
00:02:59,971 --> 00:03:01,556
There's no way I can do it.

32
00:03:06,269 --> 00:03:07,604
CENTER DIRECTOR
MAHO KIRYU

33
00:03:15,320 --> 00:03:16,988
Oh! Dr. Mizusawa?

34
00:03:17,071 --> 00:03:19,115
I'm Masumi Mizusawa.

35
00:03:19,198 --> 00:03:20,700
Call me Masumi.

36
00:03:20,783 --> 00:03:21,784
I'm Kiryu.

37
00:03:21,868 --> 00:03:23,870
- Pleasure to meet you.
- Same here.

38
00:03:24,495 --> 00:03:25,455
Huh?

39
00:03:26,164 --> 00:03:28,249
- Did you just come from the airport?
- Yes.

40
00:03:29,250 --> 00:03:31,377
Are you okay with your jet lag?

41
00:03:31,461 --> 00:03:33,254
Well… I don't know.

42
00:03:33,338 --> 00:03:37,926
You know, jet lag is like rigor mortis.

43
00:03:38,718 --> 00:03:40,595
Jet lag is like rigor mortis?

44
00:03:41,262 --> 00:03:42,555
What do you mean?

45
00:03:42,639 --> 00:03:43,514
Well…

46
00:03:44,015 --> 00:03:47,101
Jet lag doesn't happen
just because of time.

47
00:03:47,185 --> 00:03:50,313
It depends on light exposure
and the amount of sleep.

48
00:03:50,813 --> 00:03:53,566
Rigor mortis isn't determined
by time alone either.

49
00:03:53,650 --> 00:03:56,945
It changes based on temperature,
humidity, and posture.

50
00:03:57,028 --> 00:04:01,074
In other words, both depend
not just on time, but on conditions.

51
00:04:04,077 --> 00:04:05,119
Oh, okay.

52
00:04:06,287 --> 00:04:07,247
Right…

53
00:04:07,330 --> 00:04:08,164
Good.

54
00:04:10,750 --> 00:04:14,629
It finally starts tomorrow,
the medical examiner system.

55
00:04:17,423 --> 00:04:19,676
Ms. Dojima, should we call them?

56
00:04:19,759 --> 00:04:20,718
Call who?

57
00:04:20,802 --> 00:04:23,012
You know, the new system starting today,

58
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:25,974
where we have to report
all abnormal deaths

59
00:04:26,057 --> 00:04:28,726
to that, uh, medical examiner.

60
00:04:28,810 --> 00:04:31,354
Oh, that ridiculous system.

61
00:04:31,437 --> 00:04:33,189
No need to call them.

62
00:04:33,273 --> 00:04:34,107
Yes, ma'am!

63
00:04:34,190 --> 00:04:36,943
At this hour, no one would even
answer the phone, right?

64
00:04:37,026 --> 00:04:38,111
Call them then.

65
00:04:38,194 --> 00:04:40,363
It will prove
that we tried to contact them.

66
00:04:40,446 --> 00:04:42,156
Yes, ma'am! I will call them!

67
00:04:44,993 --> 00:04:45,868
They answered!

68
00:04:45,952 --> 00:04:47,578
Sorry to keep you waiting.

69
00:04:47,662 --> 00:04:48,663
It's fine.

70
00:04:48,746 --> 00:04:51,791
Decomposition doesn't progress much
at this hour.

71
00:04:53,167 --> 00:04:54,002
What?

72
00:04:54,919 --> 00:04:55,837
Hello.

73
00:05:22,822 --> 00:05:24,240
Who are you? What are you--

74
00:05:24,324 --> 00:05:25,408
Hey, stop!

75
00:05:25,491 --> 00:05:27,827
- He's the medical examiner.
- Huh?

76
00:05:27,910 --> 00:05:30,163
What's that? I wasn't told about it.

77
00:05:30,246 --> 00:05:31,706
I'm the supervisor, Kiryu.

78
00:05:32,415 --> 00:05:34,625
With the new system, any unusual deaths

79
00:05:34,709 --> 00:05:37,253
must first be examined by
a forensic pathologist.

80
00:05:37,336 --> 00:05:38,880
The medical examiner will--

81
00:05:39,881 --> 00:05:40,798
Um…

82
00:05:44,510 --> 00:05:47,513
The deceased's mother
was the first to discover the body.

83
00:05:50,183 --> 00:05:52,226
His clothes are wet.

84
00:05:52,310 --> 00:05:54,312
Keitaro Aikawa, 17 years old.

85
00:05:54,395 --> 00:05:56,022
He didn't come home by dawn,

86
00:05:56,105 --> 00:05:59,567
so his mother got worried, searched
the neighborhood, and found him here.

87
00:05:59,650 --> 00:06:01,944
She called 119 and performed CPR.

88
00:06:02,028 --> 00:06:05,656
They determined he was clearly
already dead, so he wasn't transported.

89
00:06:05,740 --> 00:06:06,949
Found a smartphone.

90
00:06:07,033 --> 00:06:09,368
The pond is about 40 centimeters deep.

91
00:06:09,452 --> 00:06:10,661
- This is murder.
- Yes.

92
00:06:10,745 --> 00:06:13,664
There's no way someone drowns
in a pond this shallow.

93
00:06:14,707 --> 00:06:16,709
I'm sorry to bother you at a tough time.

94
00:06:16,793 --> 00:06:19,670
May I ask about the situation
when you found your son--

95
00:06:19,754 --> 00:06:21,672
Hey, don't… I'm sorry, Ma'am.

96
00:06:21,756 --> 00:06:22,840
Back off.

97
00:06:23,549 --> 00:06:24,634
Doctor.

98
00:06:24,717 --> 00:06:27,470
Could you stop interfering
in the investigation?

99
00:06:29,097 --> 00:06:30,389
I'm not interfering.

100
00:06:30,473 --> 00:06:31,307
What?

101
00:06:31,390 --> 00:06:32,850
You just did.

102
00:06:32,934 --> 00:06:35,937
This is a legitimate investigation
based on the authority

103
00:06:36,020 --> 00:06:38,314
granted to a medical examiner.

104
00:06:39,774 --> 00:06:41,109
Supervisor.

105
00:06:41,818 --> 00:06:43,653
Care to explain what's going on?

106
00:06:46,364 --> 00:06:49,075
In order to determine the cause of death,

107
00:06:49,158 --> 00:06:51,661
medical examiners
are granted investigative rights.

108
00:06:51,744 --> 00:06:53,329
Are you playing detective?

109
00:06:53,412 --> 00:06:56,582
Also, under this system,
all abnormal deaths must be evaluated,

110
00:06:56,666 --> 00:06:59,252
and the medical examiner
decides if an autopsy is needed.

111
00:06:59,335 --> 00:07:01,003
It's clearly a murder.

112
00:07:01,087 --> 00:07:02,755
It is, it is a murder!

113
00:07:02,839 --> 00:07:06,217
We still don't know
whether it's a homicide.

114
00:07:10,346 --> 00:07:11,305
You're in my way.

115
00:07:37,915 --> 00:07:40,376
Why is a bureaucrat the director here?

116
00:07:41,627 --> 00:07:42,462
What?

117
00:07:42,962 --> 00:07:44,964
Do you even have a medical license?

118
00:07:45,047 --> 00:07:46,340
Do you?

119
00:07:48,217 --> 00:07:52,889
No, I don't, but this is not only
a medical institution, it's also part of

120
00:07:52,972 --> 00:07:56,184
the country's policy
in determining the cause of death.

121
00:07:56,267 --> 00:07:59,353
There's a document from the Ministry
about autopsy regulations, right?

122
00:07:59,437 --> 00:08:00,354
Yes.

123
00:08:00,438 --> 00:08:03,149
Created by the department
overseeing the medical system.

124
00:08:03,733 --> 00:08:06,944
That document
is completely useless in the field.

125
00:08:07,445 --> 00:08:09,780
You don't say.

126
00:08:10,281 --> 00:08:11,574
Really?

127
00:08:12,909 --> 00:08:14,118
Of course, it is.

128
00:08:14,202 --> 00:08:17,163
It was made by bureaucrats
who don't understand the field.

129
00:08:27,131 --> 00:08:28,299
Let's begin.

130
00:09:00,248 --> 00:09:01,791
Are you okay?

131
00:09:01,874 --> 00:09:03,167
I'm totally fine.

132
00:09:04,710 --> 00:09:07,255
The cause of death is drowning.

133
00:09:07,338 --> 00:09:09,840
In a 40-centimeter-deep pond?

134
00:09:09,924 --> 00:09:12,301
- Yes.
- How could he have drowned there?

135
00:09:12,385 --> 00:09:15,263
So he drowned somewhere else
and was moved there?

136
00:09:15,346 --> 00:09:16,847
No, that doesn't add up.

137
00:09:16,931 --> 00:09:19,850
The plankton in the pond water
matches what was in his lungs.

138
00:09:19,934 --> 00:09:22,895
That means he was alive
when he entered the water.

139
00:09:22,979 --> 00:09:27,149
So he was assaulted, lost consciousness,
and then thrown into the pond?

140
00:09:27,233 --> 00:09:29,652
There were small abrasions on his palms.

141
00:09:29,735 --> 00:09:32,238
Possibly defensive injuries
from when he fell.

142
00:09:32,321 --> 00:09:35,491
That suggests he was conscious,
trying to defend himself.

143
00:09:35,575 --> 00:09:36,659
It doesn't add up.

144
00:09:36,742 --> 00:09:41,038
So then, he was pushed
into the pond while conscious?

145
00:09:41,122 --> 00:09:44,792
The pond is 40 centimeters deep.
He should have been able to stand up.

146
00:09:44,875 --> 00:09:45,918
It doesn't add up.

147
00:09:46,002 --> 00:09:49,171
Then maybe someone held his face down
while he tried to get up.

148
00:09:49,255 --> 00:09:53,551
That would leave marks on the head,
neck, and shoulders.

149
00:09:53,634 --> 00:09:55,011
It doesn't add up.

150
00:09:55,094 --> 00:09:58,431
So then how did he drown
in a 40-centimeter-deep pond?

151
00:09:58,514 --> 00:09:59,557
Who knows?

152
00:10:00,057 --> 00:10:01,601
I wonder.

153
00:10:02,351 --> 00:10:03,561
It's a mystery.

154
00:10:08,065 --> 00:10:09,066
Well, whatever.

155
00:10:10,026 --> 00:10:10,860
Then,

156
00:10:11,527 --> 00:10:13,613
what about signs of assault?

157
00:10:21,829 --> 00:10:27,251
There are injuries to the head and chest
caused by external force.

158
00:10:27,335 --> 00:10:30,588
First, on the head, the marks
are concentrated in two places.

159
00:10:30,671 --> 00:10:34,800
Likely left by a great external force,
such as from a weapon.

160
00:10:34,884 --> 00:10:37,845
As for the chest fractures,
there are three patterns.

161
00:10:37,928 --> 00:10:40,765
One was caused by CPR.

162
00:10:40,848 --> 00:10:44,268
There was no bleeding or vital reaction.

163
00:10:44,769 --> 00:10:46,562
In regard to this area,

164
00:10:46,646 --> 00:10:51,901
it shows a significant loss of blood,
and was very likely caused by assault.

165
00:10:51,984 --> 00:10:53,694
And the last one

166
00:10:53,778 --> 00:10:56,614
is one that can't be explained
by either of the other two.

167
00:10:58,282 --> 00:11:02,953
It does not show a strong vital reaction,
but there was something.

168
00:11:03,037 --> 00:11:06,874
This mark shows the slightest
amount of vital reaction.

169
00:11:06,957 --> 00:11:09,168
Is that the clue to
determining it was homicide?

170
00:11:09,251 --> 00:11:11,253
I don't know if it will or not.

171
00:11:11,337 --> 00:11:15,925
But it might be a piece of the puzzle
to solve the mystery.

172
00:11:18,928 --> 00:11:21,931
Anyway, solve it quickly.

173
00:11:22,014 --> 00:11:23,682
- Supervisor.
- Yes?

174
00:11:24,266 --> 00:11:26,477
Do your job and supervise.

175
00:11:36,112 --> 00:11:37,238
What's that?

176
00:11:38,030 --> 00:11:40,741
The content of the notebook by the pond.

177
00:11:40,825 --> 00:11:42,326
<i>The phone next to it</i>

178
00:11:42,410 --> 00:11:45,037
was the one that belonged to
Keitaro Aikawa.

179
00:11:45,121 --> 00:11:47,289
Then the phone in the pond…

180
00:11:47,373 --> 00:11:48,874
Still being verified.

181
00:11:51,460 --> 00:11:53,921
Does anyone know what this means?

182
00:11:54,422 --> 00:11:56,674
For now, it's a mystery.

183
00:11:56,757 --> 00:12:00,261
We identified the owner of the phone.

184
00:12:00,344 --> 00:12:02,721
- What?
- Ryoya Sakagami, 17 years old.

185
00:12:02,805 --> 00:12:04,181
One arrest for marijuana dealing.

186
00:12:04,265 --> 00:12:05,850
He's a member of a group

187
00:12:05,933 --> 00:12:08,936
<i>based out of Club Heads</i>
<i>that engages in fraud and drug dealing.</i>

188
00:12:16,735 --> 00:12:18,112
Why are you running away?

189
00:12:20,614 --> 00:12:21,490
Hey!

190
00:12:24,368 --> 00:12:27,037
Police! Nobody move!

191
00:12:34,712 --> 00:12:38,424
When was the last time
you saw Ryoya Sakagami?

192
00:12:39,216 --> 00:12:41,677
You were having him sell marijuana,
were you not?

193
00:12:41,760 --> 00:12:43,345
Don't know him.

194
00:12:43,429 --> 00:12:46,765
Cut the crap! Don't cover for a murderer!

195
00:12:47,266 --> 00:12:48,476
Murderer?

196
00:12:49,518 --> 00:12:50,394
Ryoya?

197
00:12:51,770 --> 00:12:52,938
Who did he kill?

198
00:12:53,022 --> 00:12:55,774
- Aikawa--
- A 17-year-old boy.

199
00:13:00,404 --> 00:13:01,447
You don't mean…

200
00:13:02,615 --> 00:13:03,824
Keitaro?

201
00:13:07,912 --> 00:13:09,830
How do you know that?

202
00:13:10,581 --> 00:13:12,625
Was he one of your group too?

203
00:13:13,918 --> 00:13:15,336
Any marijuana show up?

204
00:13:15,419 --> 00:13:16,670
Initially not,

205
00:13:16,754 --> 00:13:19,423
but when we retested
using liquid chromatography,

206
00:13:19,507 --> 00:13:23,260
marijuana was detected
in Keitaro Aikawa's blood and urine.

207
00:13:23,344 --> 00:13:24,386
I knew it.

208
00:13:24,470 --> 00:13:26,138
Huh? What does that mean?

209
00:13:26,222 --> 00:13:28,974
<i>Keitaro Aikawa</i>
<i>was part of a marijuana trafficking group.</i>

210
00:13:29,058 --> 00:13:32,603
<i>He and one of the members, Ryoya Sakagami,</i>
<i>ran off with the marijuana.</i>

211
00:13:32,686 --> 00:13:35,606
Then, they may have had
a falling out, and he was killed.

212
00:13:35,689 --> 00:13:39,652
<i>We're currently tracking Ryoya Sakagami</i>
<i>as a key person of interest.</i>

213
00:13:39,735 --> 00:13:42,363
I'm going to Keitaro Aikawa's home.

214
00:13:42,446 --> 00:13:44,865
- What's that?
- Some questions need answers.

215
00:13:44,949 --> 00:13:46,909
The numbers and arrows in the notebook,

216
00:13:46,992 --> 00:13:49,245
the weak vital signs
of the chest fracture,

217
00:13:49,328 --> 00:13:51,997
and why he drowned
in a 40-centimeter-deep pond.

218
00:13:52,081 --> 00:13:54,416
There may be pieces there
that solve these mysteries.

219
00:13:54,500 --> 00:13:55,834
Hey, Supervisor!

220
00:13:55,918 --> 00:13:59,255
Medical examiners are granted
investigative rights to gather info--

221
00:13:59,338 --> 00:14:00,965
- Hold on!
- Wait!

222
00:14:07,680 --> 00:14:08,931
SONGWRITING NOTES VOL 3

223
00:14:10,808 --> 00:14:12,226
SONGWRITING NOTES VOL 3

224
00:14:24,363 --> 00:14:26,073
DID THE SOUND GET WORSE??

225
00:14:30,035 --> 00:14:31,161
IT'S NOT FAIR

226
00:14:31,245 --> 00:14:32,371
GOD SAVE ME

227
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:34,707
WHY?

228
00:14:34,790 --> 00:14:36,125
I'M SCARED… REALLY SCARED

229
00:14:39,128 --> 00:14:40,212
IT'S OVER

230
00:14:40,296 --> 00:14:41,755
I'M SO, SO SCARED

231
00:14:41,839 --> 00:14:43,132
SHIT SHIT SHIT

232
00:14:50,639 --> 00:14:51,682
Ms. Dojima.

233
00:14:51,765 --> 00:14:53,392
No marijuana was found.

234
00:14:56,186 --> 00:14:57,062
Let's go.

235
00:14:57,146 --> 00:14:58,022
Okay.

236
00:15:05,779 --> 00:15:09,033
Did Keitaro like music?

237
00:15:09,783 --> 00:15:11,911
If you're done, leave already.

238
00:15:25,466 --> 00:15:27,176
Man, I'm exhausted.

239
00:15:27,259 --> 00:15:29,803
Today felt insanely long. Way too long.

240
00:15:30,596 --> 00:15:32,806
Being demoted was humiliating enough,

241
00:15:32,890 --> 00:15:35,601
but going out into the field
made it even worse.

242
00:15:35,684 --> 00:15:37,394
I really can't do anything.

243
00:15:39,688 --> 00:15:42,483
I'm just there. Just watching.
But I'm the one in charge.

244
00:15:42,566 --> 00:15:44,485
I want to go back to my old job.

245
00:15:45,152 --> 00:15:47,780
There's no way
I'm stuck in the field forever, right?

246
00:15:49,031 --> 00:15:51,116
This is Medical Examiner Japan.

247
00:16:09,468 --> 00:16:12,596
He really liked music.

248
00:16:14,515 --> 00:16:15,933
It sounds silly, but…

249
00:16:17,351 --> 00:16:20,229
he used to say he wanted to be a musician…

250
00:16:22,231 --> 00:16:23,190
Even though

251
00:16:24,692 --> 00:16:27,736
becoming one
is harder than winning the lottery.

252
00:16:29,488 --> 00:16:30,406
But

253
00:16:31,448 --> 00:16:32,449
then…

254
00:16:34,618 --> 00:16:36,370
his hearing went bad.

255
00:16:39,206 --> 00:16:40,332
He said

256
00:16:41,709 --> 00:16:43,544
he was giving up on music.

257
00:16:45,337 --> 00:16:47,506
He had worked so hard at it,

258
00:16:48,173 --> 00:16:49,133
<i>so I think</i>

259
00:16:50,009 --> 00:16:51,677
<i>it was a massive shock to him.</i>

260
00:16:57,016 --> 00:16:58,142
Around that time,

261
00:16:59,977 --> 00:17:00,936
Ryoya…

262
00:17:02,938 --> 00:17:06,066
a delinquent he knew
from middle school, invited him.

263
00:17:07,109 --> 00:17:08,485
Because of him…

264
00:17:10,529 --> 00:17:12,156
Keitaro joined a bad crowd.

265
00:17:18,787 --> 00:17:19,997
Marijuana, huh?

266
00:17:21,081 --> 00:17:22,249
Maybe he…

267
00:17:26,003 --> 00:17:28,464
Maybe he was a good-for-nothing kid,

268
00:17:29,131 --> 00:17:30,507
but to me,

269
00:17:32,217 --> 00:17:33,969
he was my precious child.

270
00:17:38,515 --> 00:17:41,977
I want to know why this happened.

271
00:17:45,064 --> 00:17:46,982
I want to know what happened.

272
00:17:47,941 --> 00:17:50,110
The whole truth.

273
00:17:53,739 --> 00:17:54,865
Please.

274
00:17:56,658 --> 00:17:58,827
Find out the truth.

275
00:18:01,538 --> 00:18:03,165
If he was murdered…

276
00:18:05,918 --> 00:18:07,461
I will never forgive them.

277
00:18:10,464 --> 00:18:13,300
I have no future left, anyway.

278
00:18:14,551 --> 00:18:17,179
I'll live my life just to hate the killer.

279
00:18:46,125 --> 00:18:47,417
What are you doing?

280
00:18:52,506 --> 00:18:54,174
What? Sudoku?

281
00:19:34,923 --> 00:19:36,383
Hey, where are you going?

282
00:19:36,466 --> 00:19:38,302
- The pond.
- What?

283
00:19:38,385 --> 00:19:40,888
There might be a piece
I haven't found yet.

284
00:19:46,351 --> 00:19:47,603
What are you doing here?

285
00:19:48,061 --> 00:19:49,021
Investigating.

286
00:19:49,605 --> 00:19:51,231
Investigating, huh?

287
00:19:52,232 --> 00:19:54,109
Did the police find out anything?

288
00:19:58,780 --> 00:20:00,532
It wasn't on the day of the crime.

289
00:20:00,616 --> 00:20:03,118
He was seen with a man
thought to be Ryoya Sakagami.

290
00:20:03,202 --> 00:20:05,579
Standing opposite each other
across the pond.

291
00:20:05,662 --> 00:20:09,917
They were shouting, clapping,
and throwing stones into the water.

292
00:20:10,709 --> 00:20:13,545
Most likely, they were just high
and acting out.

293
00:20:26,308 --> 00:20:28,477
Oh, it's Ms. Dojima. Excuse me.

294
00:20:28,560 --> 00:20:29,686
Don't answer.

295
00:20:29,770 --> 00:20:31,647
- No, but--
- I said don't answer it.

296
00:20:35,150 --> 00:20:36,193
What?

297
00:21:19,778 --> 00:21:20,946
The pieces

298
00:21:21,780 --> 00:21:22,781
might be…

299
00:21:25,033 --> 00:21:26,326
coming together.

300
00:21:40,882 --> 00:21:41,758
Hey!

301
00:21:43,552 --> 00:21:44,594
Damn it!

302
00:21:46,305 --> 00:21:47,597
Let me go!

303
00:21:49,891 --> 00:21:51,059
Now what?

304
00:21:51,143 --> 00:21:53,729
<i>- I would like you to check something.</i>
- What?

305
00:21:53,812 --> 00:21:57,190
About the apps on Keitaro Aikawa's phone.

306
00:21:57,274 --> 00:21:58,400
Look, forget it.

307
00:21:58,483 --> 00:22:01,570
They caught Ryoya Sakagami,
and the interrogation is about to start.

308
00:22:01,653 --> 00:22:03,238
I'll be right there!

309
00:22:05,157 --> 00:22:07,534
- You're even coming to the interrogation?
<i>- Yes.</i>

310
00:22:07,617 --> 00:22:11,788
Based on the legitimate authority
granted to a medical examiner--

311
00:22:11,872 --> 00:22:13,332
Enough!

312
00:22:13,415 --> 00:22:14,875
Fine, I get it.

313
00:22:16,043 --> 00:22:19,546
You went to the pond on April 6th, right?

314
00:22:22,215 --> 00:22:24,051
What happened there?

315
00:22:29,222 --> 00:22:30,724
What did you do?

316
00:22:35,812 --> 00:22:37,314
I didn't go to the pond.

317
00:22:37,397 --> 00:22:40,442
Then why was your phone found in the pond?

318
00:22:47,991 --> 00:22:49,034
Excuse me.

319
00:22:49,117 --> 00:22:51,828
May I ask a question?

320
00:22:59,252 --> 00:23:00,378
Go ahead.

321
00:23:12,516 --> 00:23:14,101
Do you know

322
00:23:14,893 --> 00:23:15,936
what this is?

323
00:23:22,734 --> 00:23:23,985
You know

324
00:23:25,237 --> 00:23:26,988
what this means, don't you?

325
00:23:34,913 --> 00:23:35,747
Yes.

326
00:23:43,880 --> 00:23:44,923
And,

327
00:23:46,299 --> 00:23:51,138
there were three types of fractures
on Keitaro Aikawa's chest.

328
00:23:52,764 --> 00:23:53,807
The first

329
00:23:54,516 --> 00:23:55,976
was from being assaulted.

330
00:23:57,352 --> 00:23:58,520
The second

331
00:23:59,062 --> 00:24:02,107
was from his mother performing CPR.

332
00:24:05,193 --> 00:24:06,403
The third one…

333
00:24:08,405 --> 00:24:09,739
was from you, right?

334
00:24:20,834 --> 00:24:22,210
What happened?

335
00:24:30,302 --> 00:24:31,678
I'm sorry.

336
00:24:35,223 --> 00:24:36,266
I'm sorry.

337
00:24:37,893 --> 00:24:39,227
I'm sorry.

338
00:24:43,148 --> 00:24:44,566
I'm sorry.

339
00:24:49,654 --> 00:24:51,031
I'm sorry.

340
00:24:52,115 --> 00:24:53,450
I'm sorry.

341
00:25:01,666 --> 00:25:05,921
I will now explain
the cause of Keitaro's death.

342
00:25:06,963 --> 00:25:08,131
Please.

343
00:25:09,424 --> 00:25:10,800
We determined

344
00:25:10,884 --> 00:25:13,386
that the cause of death was drowning.

345
00:25:14,971 --> 00:25:18,350
First, around 5:00 p.m. the prior evening,

346
00:25:18,433 --> 00:25:20,977
<i>he was struck in the head,</i>
<i>causing a hematoma,</i>

347
00:25:21,061 --> 00:25:22,771
<i>essentially a lump.</i>

348
00:25:23,271 --> 00:25:27,442
Left alone, it was an injury
that would have healed naturally.

349
00:25:29,611 --> 00:25:32,822
After that, Keitaro came to this pond.

350
00:25:34,282 --> 00:25:36,409
This pond has a bridge spanning it,

351
00:25:36,493 --> 00:25:38,703
and the surrounding slopes
form a bowl shape,

352
00:25:38,787 --> 00:25:41,706
creating an environment
where sound echoes easily.

353
00:25:46,795 --> 00:25:48,463
MASUMI MIZUSAWA

354
00:25:51,758 --> 00:25:54,427
The sound bounces back
from various directions,

355
00:25:54,511 --> 00:25:57,973
making you lose sense
of where it's actually coming from.

356
00:25:58,556 --> 00:26:01,309
For Keitaro, who was hard of hearing
in his left ear,

357
00:26:01,393 --> 00:26:03,478
it was particularly confusing.

358
00:26:21,705 --> 00:26:23,748
Then, at around 10:00 p.m. that night,

359
00:26:23,832 --> 00:26:26,293
<i>while Keitaro was standing</i>
<i>at the edge of the pond,</i>

360
00:26:26,376 --> 00:26:28,420
<i>a motorcycle horn honked.</i>

361
00:26:29,796 --> 00:26:34,134
A horn is designed to resonate loudly
in a specific direction ahead.

362
00:26:34,676 --> 00:26:37,470
<i>Keitaro got startled by it,</i>

363
00:26:37,554 --> 00:26:40,432
<i>feeling as though the sound source</i>
<i>was close to him.</i>

364
00:26:40,515 --> 00:26:44,436
<i>He instinctively tried to avoid</i>
<i>the loud noise from an unknown direction,</i>

365
00:26:44,519 --> 00:26:46,896
<i>and it is likely that he slipped.</i>

366
00:26:46,980 --> 00:26:48,148
<i>He fell into the pond</i>

367
00:26:48,231 --> 00:26:50,775
<i>and hit his head on the water's surface.</i>

368
00:26:51,484 --> 00:26:52,652
<i>At that moment,</i>

369
00:26:52,736 --> 00:26:56,197
<i>a second impact was delivered</i>
<i>to a brain that had already been damaged.</i>

370
00:26:56,281 --> 00:27:00,577
This is known as Second Impact Syndrome.

371
00:27:01,578 --> 00:27:05,707
If the brain receives a second blow
before it has recovered from the first,

372
00:27:06,333 --> 00:27:11,671
even a minor force can amplify the damage
and lead to a fatal outcome.

373
00:27:12,255 --> 00:27:13,548
<i>In Keitaro's case,</i>

374
00:27:13,631 --> 00:27:17,218
<i>he suffered a severe concussion</i>
<i>and lost consciousness.</i>

375
00:27:17,844 --> 00:27:19,054
As a result,

376
00:27:19,929 --> 00:27:24,100
he drowned in a pond
only 40 centimeters deep.

377
00:27:26,061 --> 00:27:26,895
What?

378
00:27:28,813 --> 00:27:29,689
In other words,

379
00:27:31,316 --> 00:27:34,778
it was a tragic accident resulting
from a series of coincidences.

380
00:27:38,031 --> 00:27:39,115
An accident?

381
00:27:46,664 --> 00:27:49,209
If he hadn't been hit in the head,

382
00:27:49,292 --> 00:27:50,919
he wouldn't have died, right?

383
00:27:52,879 --> 00:27:55,256
If that horn hadn't been honked,

384
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:56,883
he wouldn't have died.

385
00:27:58,009 --> 00:28:01,346
He died because someone did those things,
didn't he?

386
00:28:03,890 --> 00:28:06,643
And yet, you call it an accident.

387
00:28:09,938 --> 00:28:11,523
I won't accept that.

388
00:28:12,482 --> 00:28:14,025
I can't let it be.

389
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:17,487
Keitaro was murdered.

390
00:28:19,406 --> 00:28:21,366
Wasn't it Ryoya who honked the horn?

391
00:28:21,449 --> 00:28:23,868
I know he rides a bike.

392
00:28:23,952 --> 00:28:26,204
That boy killed Keitaro, right?

393
00:28:26,287 --> 00:28:28,706
Arrest him. Aren't you the police?

394
00:28:28,790 --> 00:28:31,000
I understand how you feel.

395
00:28:31,084 --> 00:28:33,169
But based on the objective facts,

396
00:28:33,253 --> 00:28:36,548
the police are treating this case
as an accident.

397
00:28:36,631 --> 00:28:40,927
We have released the person of interest
after questioning.

398
00:28:41,010 --> 00:28:42,804
That's not right.

399
00:28:43,430 --> 00:28:45,390
Keitaro is dead,

400
00:28:45,473 --> 00:28:47,809
so why does he get to live a normal life?

401
00:28:50,311 --> 00:28:51,813
I understand how you feel,

402
00:28:52,313 --> 00:28:56,818
but these are the facts
derived from a forensic perspective.

403
00:28:58,027 --> 00:28:59,070
I told you

404
00:29:00,488 --> 00:29:02,866
I can't accept that.

405
00:29:11,332 --> 00:29:13,376
Shouldn't we tell her about it?

406
00:29:15,587 --> 00:29:16,671
That thing?

407
00:29:24,679 --> 00:29:25,889
Yes.

408
00:29:35,982 --> 00:29:39,986
My job is to convey the results
of the cause-of-death investigation.

409
00:29:41,321 --> 00:29:44,532
Anything else is not for me to say.

410
00:29:46,701 --> 00:29:47,660
However…

411
00:29:49,913 --> 00:29:52,165
you are the supervisor, Ms. Kiryu.

412
00:29:54,501 --> 00:29:57,086
If there is something else
you want to convey,

413
00:29:57,170 --> 00:30:00,048
please use your own judgment.

414
00:30:14,979 --> 00:30:16,397
<i>But to me,</i>

415
00:30:16,481 --> 00:30:18,733
he was my precious child.

416
00:30:18,817 --> 00:30:20,860
I want to know what happened.

417
00:30:21,444 --> 00:30:23,363
The whole truth.

418
00:30:34,791 --> 00:30:38,127
The one who honked the horn
was Ryoya Sakagami.

419
00:30:38,711 --> 00:30:39,504
Hey.

420
00:30:40,755 --> 00:30:42,131
What are you doing?

421
00:30:42,757 --> 00:30:44,884
It's the decision of the supervisor.

422
00:30:47,512 --> 00:30:48,930
Do what you want.

423
00:30:49,013 --> 00:30:51,266
The police won't take responsibility.

424
00:31:00,108 --> 00:31:01,276
Ms. Aikawa…

425
00:31:02,777 --> 00:31:06,906
Keitaro hadn't given up on his dream.

426
00:31:08,241 --> 00:31:09,909
How could you know that?

427
00:31:11,077 --> 00:31:14,831
It's the arrows and numbers
written in the notebook.

428
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:19,544
<i>Because Keitaro</i>
<i>could only hear out of one ear,</i>

429
00:31:19,627 --> 00:31:23,965
<i>the direction sound was coming from</i>
<i>differed from the actual source.</i>

430
00:31:27,635 --> 00:31:30,138
<i>He was using this pond</i>
<i>to confirm that deviation,</i>

431
00:31:30,221 --> 00:31:32,682
<i>and was trying to correct it himself.</i>

432
00:31:35,226 --> 00:31:37,353
Close! You're almost there.

433
00:31:41,524 --> 00:31:43,484
<i>The arrows are the direction of the sound,</i>

434
00:31:43,568 --> 00:31:45,904
<i>and the numbers represent</i>
<i>the angle of the shift.</i>

435
00:31:47,947 --> 00:31:49,616
You're amazing, Keitaro.

436
00:31:49,699 --> 00:31:51,618
You're making progress.

437
00:31:52,577 --> 00:31:54,662
I shouldn't have invited you
into the gang.

438
00:31:55,622 --> 00:31:56,748
I'm really sorry.

439
00:32:00,293 --> 00:32:03,129
Do you think I can still be a musician?

440
00:32:05,548 --> 00:32:06,716
You will.

441
00:32:07,634 --> 00:32:08,885
If anyone can, it's you.

442
00:32:10,094 --> 00:32:11,846
So you have to get out of the gang.

443
00:32:14,974 --> 00:32:15,892
Right.

444
00:32:17,685 --> 00:32:18,603
But,

445
00:32:19,437 --> 00:32:21,648
my mom used to say all the time

446
00:32:21,731 --> 00:32:26,694
that becoming a musician
is harder than winning the lottery.

447
00:32:30,949 --> 00:32:34,494
And then, on that day, Keitaro was…

448
00:32:39,040 --> 00:32:39,874
I…

449
00:32:41,793 --> 00:32:43,211
want out.

450
00:32:43,962 --> 00:32:44,921
I don't want…

451
00:32:47,131 --> 00:32:48,675
to sell marijuana anymore.

452
00:32:59,102 --> 00:33:00,269
Come here!

453
00:33:01,396 --> 00:33:04,649
<i>The trace amount of marijuana</i>
<i>detected in Keitaro</i>

454
00:33:04,732 --> 00:33:07,402
<i>was most likely from secondhand smoke.</i>

455
00:33:20,957 --> 00:33:22,959
Can't you just let Keitaro go?

456
00:33:24,752 --> 00:33:26,504
I'll sell his share too.

457
00:33:27,797 --> 00:33:28,881
Just please

458
00:33:29,924 --> 00:33:31,217
let Keitaro out.

459
00:33:42,478 --> 00:33:43,438
Please!

460
00:33:44,397 --> 00:33:45,231
Hey.

461
00:33:45,982 --> 00:33:46,983
Hey!

462
00:33:47,066 --> 00:33:48,609
Stand up, asshole.

463
00:33:49,193 --> 00:33:50,611
Don't fuck with us!

464
00:33:52,864 --> 00:33:54,157
Please…

465
00:33:55,158 --> 00:33:56,034
Please!

466
00:33:56,117 --> 00:33:57,785
- You little shit…
- Please…

467
00:33:57,869 --> 00:33:58,745
Take that!

468
00:34:03,458 --> 00:34:04,375
Bastard!

469
00:34:04,459 --> 00:34:05,376
Please.

470
00:34:10,882 --> 00:34:12,133
Please.

471
00:34:12,216 --> 00:34:13,885
You little shit…

472
00:34:18,473 --> 00:34:19,557
Please.

473
00:34:23,269 --> 00:34:24,228
In exchange,

474
00:34:24,312 --> 00:34:27,023
you bring in three million yen
in one week.

475
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:39,660
Thank you!

476
00:34:43,122 --> 00:34:44,540
Thank you!

477
00:34:49,003 --> 00:34:50,630
Thank you!

478
00:35:10,191 --> 00:35:11,442
Lame.

479
00:35:16,072 --> 00:35:17,448
He honked his horn

480
00:35:19,075 --> 00:35:21,702
because he wanted to tell Keitaro
the good news.

481
00:35:25,039 --> 00:35:28,126
He was just happy and honked it.

482
00:35:36,759 --> 00:35:37,718
Hey!

483
00:35:38,511 --> 00:35:40,304
Quit messing around.

484
00:35:48,646 --> 00:35:49,939
Keitaro!

485
00:35:50,022 --> 00:35:52,024
Hey! Keitaro? Hey!

486
00:35:52,108 --> 00:35:53,067
Hey!

487
00:35:56,487 --> 00:35:57,613
Keitaro!

488
00:35:57,697 --> 00:35:59,615
Keitaro!

489
00:35:59,699 --> 00:36:01,117
Keitaro!

490
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:03,286
Keitaro…

491
00:36:04,162 --> 00:36:06,372
Keitaro!

492
00:36:06,455 --> 00:36:07,665
Keitaro…

493
00:36:19,594 --> 00:36:21,429
<i>I thought he might have died</i>

494
00:36:22,972 --> 00:36:24,932
<i>because of the CPR I gave him.</i>

495
00:36:28,477 --> 00:36:29,896
I got scared and ran away.

496
00:36:35,776 --> 00:36:36,903
I'm sorry.

497
00:36:48,122 --> 00:36:50,082
If Ryoya had called an ambulance,

498
00:36:51,334 --> 00:36:52,752
would he have lived?

499
00:36:55,004 --> 00:36:55,922
No.

500
00:36:58,049 --> 00:36:59,592
Even if he had called one,

501
00:37:00,593 --> 00:37:02,720
the result would have been the same.

502
00:37:05,473 --> 00:37:08,601
There was a fracture
on Keitaro's chest that showed

503
00:37:08,684 --> 00:37:11,395
a very slight vital reaction.

504
00:37:12,521 --> 00:37:13,481
That was

505
00:37:14,649 --> 00:37:17,026
from the CPR performed

506
00:37:18,027 --> 00:37:19,987
by Ryoya Sakagami.

507
00:37:21,864 --> 00:37:25,117
The fact that the vital reaction
was so minimal

508
00:37:25,201 --> 00:37:28,704
proves that the CPR
was performed immediately after death.

509
00:37:28,788 --> 00:37:31,624
In other words, it means that Keitaro

510
00:37:33,334 --> 00:37:35,294
had already passed away.

511
00:37:48,432 --> 00:37:49,475
Ms. Aikawa.

512
00:37:52,395 --> 00:37:53,938
CPR…

513
00:37:56,190 --> 00:37:57,650
was performed twice.

514
00:38:00,695 --> 00:38:06,200
The two sets of marks
on Keitaro's chest were both

515
00:38:07,285 --> 00:38:08,577
left by people

516
00:38:09,996 --> 00:38:13,791
who desperately wanted him to live.

517
00:38:18,838 --> 00:38:20,131
Keitaro…

518
00:38:20,798 --> 00:38:22,133
Keitaro!

519
00:38:22,633 --> 00:38:23,843
Please!

520
00:38:24,593 --> 00:38:25,594
Keitaro!

521
00:38:26,262 --> 00:38:27,555
Stay with me, Keitaro!

522
00:38:27,638 --> 00:38:28,889
Keitaro!

523
00:38:29,682 --> 00:38:30,599
Keitaro!

524
00:38:30,683 --> 00:38:32,059
Keitaro!

525
00:38:32,143 --> 00:38:33,811
Please!

526
00:38:33,894 --> 00:38:35,354
Keitaro!

527
00:38:35,438 --> 00:38:36,522
Keitaro!

528
00:38:36,605 --> 00:38:37,690
Keitaro!

529
00:38:37,773 --> 00:38:39,191
Keitaro!

530
00:38:40,067 --> 00:38:41,569
Keitaro!

531
00:38:41,652 --> 00:38:42,945
Keitaro!

532
00:38:49,952 --> 00:38:51,037
So…

533
00:38:56,125 --> 00:38:58,169
you're telling me to forgive him?

534
00:39:05,051 --> 00:39:06,844
Don't make it sound so simple.

535
00:40:28,801 --> 00:40:30,845
Dying like that…

536
00:40:32,930 --> 00:40:35,808
is harder than winning
the lottery, isn't it?

537
00:40:45,484 --> 00:40:46,527
I'm sorry.

538
00:40:55,327 --> 00:40:56,704
I'm sorry.

539
00:40:58,414 --> 00:40:59,582
I'm sorry.

540
00:41:00,374 --> 00:41:01,417
I'm sorry.

541
00:41:05,379 --> 00:41:06,547
I'm sorry.

542
00:41:10,176 --> 00:41:11,302
I'm sorry.

543
00:41:18,392 --> 00:41:19,643
I'm sorry…

544
00:41:49,548 --> 00:41:52,259
Regarding the pickup
of Keitaro Aikawa's body,

545
00:41:52,343 --> 00:41:55,721
the funeral director should be here
in about 20 minutes.

546
00:41:55,804 --> 00:41:57,681
Okay. Thank you.

547
00:42:06,649 --> 00:42:09,401
Thank you for today.

548
00:42:14,448 --> 00:42:15,282
But,

549
00:42:17,117 --> 00:42:18,702
I think my decision today

550
00:42:20,204 --> 00:42:21,539
was one step away

551
00:42:23,290 --> 00:42:27,211
from rubbing the bereaved mother
the wrong way.

552
00:42:39,557 --> 00:42:40,724
In America,

553
00:42:41,725 --> 00:42:44,770
they call the deceased a "Loved One."

554
00:42:48,023 --> 00:42:49,066
Loved One?

555
00:42:56,949 --> 00:42:58,492
Does that mean someone…

556
00:43:00,494 --> 00:43:02,288
who was important

557
00:43:04,373 --> 00:43:06,041
to someone else?

558
00:43:09,378 --> 00:43:10,713
The term…

559
00:43:13,591 --> 00:43:14,800
is hard to translate.

560
00:43:16,594 --> 00:43:17,595
What?

561
00:43:20,347 --> 00:43:22,474
It's a word only used at the scene,

562
00:43:23,934 --> 00:43:26,520
and also a word only for oneself.

563
00:43:28,897 --> 00:43:31,317
A word only for oneself?

564
00:43:33,152 --> 00:43:34,153
Yes.

565
00:43:37,615 --> 00:43:39,366
Only you can decide

566
00:43:40,534 --> 00:43:42,911
what it means.

567
00:43:44,913 --> 00:43:46,999
Your decision today

568
00:43:47,750 --> 00:43:53,172
was your own way
of facing a Loved One, wasn't it?

569
00:44:36,131 --> 00:44:37,466
The death was caused by a fall.

570
00:44:37,549 --> 00:44:38,759
Is it fun?

571
00:44:38,842 --> 00:44:41,261
Talking about someone's death like that?

572
00:44:41,345 --> 00:44:43,889
<i>If I had known it would be</i>
<i>the last time, I--</i>

573
00:44:43,972 --> 00:44:45,474
It's not over yet.

574
00:44:45,557 --> 00:44:47,017
You're a forensic pathologist.

575
00:44:47,101 --> 00:44:49,937
<i>There may still be a piece</i>
<i>we haven't found yet.</i>

576
00:44:50,020 --> 00:44:50,896
Subtitle translation by: Maslin F.
